Peel and chop the @sweet potato{1}(peeled and chopped into 1cm chunks). Peel and grate the @garlic clove{2}(peeled and grated) or use a #garlic press{}.

Zest and cut the @lime{1/2}(zested and cut into wedges). Drain and rinse the @chickpeas{1%carton} in a #sieve{}.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{drizzle} in a large #saucepan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @yellow Thai style paste{45%g}, @Thai style spice mix{1%sachet} and @garlic{2%cloves}(minced). Stir and cook until fragrant, ~{1-2%mins}.

Add the @diced British chicken breast{260%g}, sweet potato and chickpeas to the pan, then stir in the @vegetable stock paste{10%g}, @coconut milk{200%ml}, @peanut butter{30%g} and @water{125%ml}(for the curry).

Stir the sauce thoroughly to combine, ~{2-3%mins}. Bring to the boil, then reduce to a simmer.

Cover with a #lid{} and simmer, stirring occasionally, until the sweet potato is tender, ~{15-20%mins}. Add a splash of water if you feel it needs it.

== Zesty Basmati Rice ==

Meanwhile, pour the @water{300%ml}(for the rice) into a medium saucepan with a tight-fitting lid.

Stir in the @basmati rice{150%g} and @salt{1/4%tsp} and bring to the boil. Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%mins}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%mins} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

== Finishing ==

Once the sweet potato is cooked, remove the lid from the curry and add the @baby spinach{40%g} a handful at a time until wilted and piping hot, ~{1-2%mins}.

Add a good squeeze of @lime juice{squeeze}(from the remaining lime) to the curry, then season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Taste and add more salt, pepper and lime juice if needed.

When everything's ready, fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and stir through the lime zest.

Share the zesty rice between your #bowls{} and spoon over the chicken and chickpea curry.

Serve with any remaining lime cut into wedges for squeezing over.

Enjoy!

